2026-04-16 12:37:22 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['switched cables indicator LED circuit branch (control module)'] hypothesis_explanation='There is a sustained high voltage (11.99 V) at the relay switched output (+) and a drastic voltage drop to 0.36 V at the entry to the load module during lamp-off intervals, even though the relay and cables themselves test as having nominal continuity and resistance. The only component between these points is the switched cables indicator LED (and its series resistor/branch). If this branch is intermittently open (for example due to a failed solder joint at the control PCB or bad contact at the series resistor or shorting of the indicator), the path for current from the relay output to the load will be broken, even if a continuity test occasionally shows a connection. Since LED operation is rapidly switching (or circuit is briefly breaking connection), this would create the observed transient loss of power despite no visible relay or cable fault and explains why the voltage collapses at the load input. This is distinct from a pure LED device fault and implicates the wiring, board trace, or soldering in the circuit branch as the root cause.'
